# Kimberley Ens Manning, ‘The Gendered Politics of Woman-Work: Rethinking Radicalism in the Great Leap Forward’, Modern China 32(3) (2006), pp. 349–384.

## ♠Point

1）I call the ideology under girding woman-work **“Marxist maternalist equality”**.（p.356）  

This framework recognized women as both producers and reproducers. It supported women’s participation in labor and politics, but at the same time insisted that women had special physiological needs and maternal duties.  

①helping women struggle for equality

②maintaining the family, protecting reproductive health, and caring for children


2）I call **“revolutionary Maoism”** the discourse that advocated the violent overcoming of self and enemy while condemning women and “their issues” as trivial, and I call the women most influenced by revolutionary Maoism “egalitarians.”（p.357）  

Within this framework, concern for women’s bodily weakness or special protections could appear trivial, distracting, or even politically backward（无关紧要/分心/政治落后）.  

①heroic sacrifice, total commitment, violent struggle  

②the revolutionary capacity to overcome both social oppression and natural limits

→The article’s key theoretical move is to show that the tension between Marxist maternalism and revolutionary Maoism did not disappear after 1949.  

1949年以后，这两套话语并没有随着国家建立而被统一，反而在基层实践中分化得更明显了。  

Manning emphasizes variation. Some women’s heads remained protective and maternalist in practice. Others denied the need for special treatment.  

*The ACWF invested heavily in women’s hygiene, medicine, obstetrics, childcare, and reproductive health, and it continued to emphasize maternal and child welfare even into 1959.

3）**Male leaders and female leaders remembered the Great Leap Forward differently**.  

①male: felt powerless in the face of extreme political pressure  

②female: denied that health protection was needed or insisted that struggle itself liberated women (had its own ideological basis)

4）**Grassroots Party building**

After 1949 the ACWF established committees, but in practice local Party organizations often did most of the recruiting and training of rural women leaders.  

Manning的观点是1949年后虽然妇联体系在建，但在很多地方，真正负责招募和训练农村妇女干部的，其实还是基层党组织（文中没有系统比较这些地区里党、妇联、青年团、农会等组织的人数、编制、活动频率、干部来源比例，也没有真正做出一种组织社会学意义上的“哪一类组织在基层更具渗透力”的硬证分析。更准确地说，她是从女干部的口述、身份轨迹和价值取向出发，推论出基层党组织的塑造力更强；这个推论有道理，但不是那种无可争辩的硬证明）。并且她指出了当时存在的其他党政部门和人民团体对妇联/妇女工作的边缘化：  

peasant associations, work teams, the Youth League, and Party membership all helped cultivate egalitarian radicalism. Women who had prior Youth League or production experience were often the least willing to do woman-work, seeing it as backward or lacking glory.  

*Zhang is the most important case: she was recruited by a work team, trained through the Youth League and local Party networks, and backed by an influential Party family.  

→Egalitarian women leaders were not simply anti-women or anti-equality. Rather, they held **a different, struggle-based understanding of equality—one shaped by Party institutions more than by Women’s Federation maternalism**.  

从基层党组织的革命文化里长出来的平等观

5）new forms of female activism（非褒义）  

Grassroots Party building in the Mao era did not always reinforce patriarchy in a simple way. It could also produce new forms of female activism—some of which were so radically egalitarian that they undermined the ACWF’s maternalist agenda and destabilized women’s organizations themselves.  

基层党组织有时也会培养出非常有行动力的女性，只不过这些女性形成的，未必是妇联期待的那种“以妇幼保护为中心”的干部，而可能是一种更激进、甚至反过来冲击妇联自身组织基础的女性革命主体。
